(chapter
  :book \"book-of-music\"
  :number 15
  :title \"Tempo, Rubato, and Listening\"
  :short-title \"tempo-rubato-listening\"
  :estimated-words 3400
  :philosopher-weave (aristotle wittgenstein-late peirce freud)

  :prose
\"There is a metronome sitting on top of the piano in nearly every practice room in the world. It is a small mechanical or electronic device that ticks a steady beat, adjustable in beats per minute. Musicians use it to check their internal tempo — to make sure they are not rushing, not dragging, not letting the tempo drift from where the composer marked it.

And then, in performance, most great musicians turn it off, or ignore it in their head, and they play the piece *not exactly in tempo*.

That looks like a contradiction. It is not. This chapter is about what tempo is, what happens when musicians shape time inside a piece, and what a listener is actually hearing when a great performance seems to breathe.

# Tempo, plainly

*Tempo* is the speed of a piece. It is measured in beats per minute (bpm). A metronome at 60 clicks once per second. A metronome at 120 clicks twice per second. When a composer writes a tempo marking at the top of a movement — *Allegro* (fast), *Andante* (walking speed), *Adagio* (slow), *Largo* (broad) — they are indicating roughly how fast the piece should feel. Some composers, from Beethoven onward, add specific metronome markings: *quarter note = 108*, meaning the quarter note gets 108 beats per minute.

The Italian tempo words are traditional and imprecise. Grove lists rough ranges: *Largo* is around 40-60 bpm, *Adagio* around 66-76, *Andante* around 76-108, *Moderato* around 108-120, *Allegro* around 120-168, *Presto* around 168-200. These ranges vary by era, by composer, and by editorial tradition. When a piece has both an Italian marking and a metronome number, the metronome number is more specific but the Italian word carries the *character* — *Allegro* means not just 'fast' but 'cheerful, brisk.' A tempo is a speed *plus* a mood.

Beethoven's own metronome markings, added late in his life for many of his major works, are notoriously fast — often faster than performers today actually play them. This has been debated by scholars for two centuries. Some argue Beethoven's metronome was miscalibrated; some argue tastes changed; some argue Beethoven had specific reasons for his markings that modern performance has drifted from. The truth is probably a mix. What we can say is: a tempo marking is not a law. It is an intention, and performers negotiate with it every time they play.

# What rubato actually is

*Rubato* — literally 'stolen' in Italian — is the practice of shaping the tempo *within* a piece: slowing down slightly, speeding up slightly, holding a moment for expressive effect, then giving the time back. The word is short for *tempo rubato*, and Chopin is the composer most associated with it.

There are two kinds of rubato that musicians distinguish:

**Melodic rubato.** The right hand plays the melody with expressive freedom — arriving slightly late on a leaning phrase, pushing forward through a rising line — while the left hand keeps steady time underneath. The two hands do not sync exactly. The melody floats over the accompaniment like a leaf on moving water. This is the rubato Chopin was famous for. His student, the pianist Ignaz Moscheles, wrote that Chopin's left hand kept 'strictly in time' while his right 'had every freedom.' It is subtle. Recorded pianists in the early twentieth century — Alfred Cortot, Ignaz Friedman, later Arthur Rubinstein — brought this style forward into the age of recording, and you can hear it clearly on their discs.

**Structural rubato.** The tempo of the whole texture — both hands, or the whole orchestra — slows and speeds as the phrase requires. A big lyrical passage broadens; a tense passage rushes forward; a quiet moment holds. This is the rubato of Wagnerian conductors like Wilhelm Furtwängler, whose tempos famously flexed across huge symphonic paragraphs. Recordings of Furtwängler conducting Beethoven's Ninth or Wagner's *Tristan* are lessons in how much a tempo can bend and still hold.

Both kinds of rubato are expressive tools. They are not sloppiness. A performer who *drifts* out of tempo unintentionally is not doing rubato; a performer who *shapes* the tempo with intent and returns to the underlying pulse is doing rubato well.

# The paradox of the metronome

Here is the paradox. Musicians practice with a metronome to develop a *steady* internal pulse. And then they use rubato in performance to *shape* that pulse. Why?

Because rubato only works if the underlying pulse is felt. If you slow down slightly and then speed up slightly, the listener can only feel the rubato *against* an implied steady tempo. If there is no steady tempo underneath, the rubato has nothing to push against — it is just erratic time. A great rubato performer is playing the shaping *and* implying the steady tempo simultaneously. The metronome, in practice, is what builds the ability to imply the steady tempo. The performance is where the shaping is added on top.

Great pianists spend years building this. Sviatoslav Richter — a Russian pianist active from the 1940s to the 1990s, one of the technical masters of the century — recorded some of his performances at what feels like completely steady tempo, and yet listeners describe them as full of feeling. Glenn Gould went the other direction: some of his Bach recordings feel almost robotic in their rhythmic precision, and yet the shaping of every phrase makes the same notes feel newly meaningful. Both approaches — the almost-steady and the strongly-shaped — can produce great performances. The bad performances are the ones where the tempo drifts without intent.

# How the same piece becomes different pieces

Let's put two recordings of Chopin's Nocturne in E-flat major, Op. 9 No. 2 side by side (you can find these easily; both are in the public domain in most countries now). Arthur Rubinstein recorded the piece several times across his career — his 1937 recording, made when he was fifty, and his 1965 recording, made when he was seventy-eight, are both considered great and are quite different from each other. The 1937 is quicker, more forward-moving, with rubato that leans in and lets go. The 1965 is slower, more inward, with rubato that holds moments longer. The notes on the page are identical. Two performances by the same pianist, twenty-eight years apart, on the same piece, sound like two different meditations on the same tune. This is what interpretation *is*: the performer bringing their whole life to the piece at the moment they play it.

Compare either Rubinstein to a performance by Vladimir Horowitz, who recorded the same Op. 9 No. 2 in the 1950s. Horowitz's rubato is more angular — quicker in the runs, sharper in the accents, more contrast between loud and soft. The piece feels more urgent. Not better or worse than Rubinstein; different. And the difference is in the *time*: how long each note is held, how the phrases lean, when the tempo pushes forward and when it pulls back.

This is why classical music lovers own multiple recordings of the same piece. Not out of completism. Because the piece is a container, and each great performer fills the container differently, and you can spend a lifetime learning what different fillings do.

# What we can do in Scheme

We can simulate rubato in a small way: take a phrase and shape the tempo across it.

```scheme
;; A simple phrase with rubato shaping — the middle of the phrase
;; slows down, then the tempo returns.

(define phrase
  '((C5 quarter) (D5 quarter) (E5 quarter) (F5 quarter) (G5 half)))

;; A rubato profile: a list of tempo scales for each note.
;; Values > 1 = slower (note gets more time). Values < 1 = faster.
(define rubato-profile
  '(1.0 1.05 1.15 1.10 1.0))     ; slow into the peak, return to tempo

(define (play-with-rubato phrase profile base-tempo)
  (for-each
    (lambda (note-and-duration scale)
      (let* ((n (car note-and-duration))
             (d (cadr note-and-duration))
             (effective-tempo (/ base-tempo scale)))
        (transport/tempo effective-tempo)
        (note-play n d)))
    phrase
    profile))

(play-with-rubato phrase rubato-profile 100)
```

That is a crude rubato — a discrete tempo change at each note. Real rubato is continuous; the tempo bends smoothly across the phrase. But the shape is right: the middle of the phrase leans and the ends stay closer to tempo. If you played the phrase through a synthesizer with this profile, you would hear something that begins to feel expressive — a phrase with breath in it, not a phrase clicked off a metronome.

# What we listen for in a performer's tempo

There are a few specific things a trained listener notices when a performer shapes time:

**Where the phrase peaks.** Most expressive phrases have a *high point* — the loudest note, the highest note, the most-emphasized moment. Performers typically time-stretch slightly around the peak: arriving at it a hair late (which creates tension), holding it a fraction longer, then releasing forward. The listener feels the peak as a moment of arrival.

**Where the phrase breathes.** Between two phrases, or at a caesura (a break in the musical thought), performers take a small breath — a fraction of a second longer than the notated rest would suggest. This is how they *punctuate*. Without it, phrases run together and the music loses its sentence structure.

**Where the tempo pushes.** In fast, urgent passages, performers often push the tempo forward — slightly faster than the metronome — to increase the sense of drive. This is called *stringendo* if it's continuous, or *accelerando* if it's a marked change.

**Where the tempo holds.** In slow, lyrical passages, performers often hold the tempo back — slightly slower — to give the melody room to sing. This is *ritardando* if marked, or *tenuto* on a single note.

These four things — peak, breath, push, hold — are the vocabulary of expressive timing. A student learning to shape phrases will practice them consciously. A great performer does them without thinking, the way a great actor delivers a line with the right pause without counting to two.

# How to listen for what you're hearing

If you are listening to a piece and want to notice the tempo shaping:

Set aside a specific recording. Not background listening; actual sitting-down attention to the music.

Pick a phrase. A four- or eight-bar melodic passage.

Listen for where the phrase feels like it *lifts*. That is usually a peak. Notice how the performer times it.

Listen for where the phrase *settles*. That is usually a resolution point. Notice how much time the performer gives it.

Listen for the *silence between phrases*. Notice whether it's short and hurried, or generous.

Then, if you have another recording of the same piece, do it again with the other recording and compare. You will start to hear how two performers make different meanings out of the same notes.

This is what classical music listeners spend decades developing — an ear for time-shaping, for the way a phrase can be shaped in a hundred subtly different ways. It's why the same piece never gets exhausted: two performances are two conversations with the same object, and there are infinitely many possible conversations.

# Tie back

Tempo is speed. Rubato is speed *shaped* over time. A great performer plays with a steady internal pulse *and* shapes the surface of the tempo expressively — the two do not contradict each other; the second only works because of the first.

If you have been listening to classical music without paying attention to time before, this chapter is an invitation. Put on a recording of a Chopin nocturne. Listen for the peaks, the breaths, the pushes, the holds. Then listen to a different recording of the same nocturne and notice what the second performer does differently.

This is the practice of listening. The pieces in the last four chapters — Rach 2, the Chopin nocturnes, the classical forms, the physical harmonic series — will all come alive under attention of this kind.

Next chapter: the concerto — a synthesis chapter that brings the whole book together on one piece.

